hands_on_practices.problem:
A surface-bound intermediate in a catalytic cycle exhibits a high-frequency X–H stretching vibration that can be modeled as a one-dimensional quantum harmonic oscillator within the harmonic approximation. The observed wavenumber for the hydrogen isotopologue is $	ilde{
u}_{	ext{H}}=3000\ \mathrm{cm}^{-1}$. Consider isotopic substitution by deuterium at this mode, such that the effective vibrating mass for this mode doubles while the local force constant remains unchanged. Assume that the vibrational frequency scales inversely with the square root of the effective mass. Using the quantum harmonic oscillator ground-state energy as the zero-point energy, estimate the change in zero-point energy upon hydrogen-to-deuterium substitution for this single mode, defined as $\Delta E_{	ext{ZPE}} = E_{	ext{ZPE}}(	ext{D}) - E_{	ext{ZPE}}(	ext{H})$, on a per-mole basis. Express your final answer in $\mathrm{kJ\,mol}^{-1}$ and round to four significant figures. Use the relations $E = h c 	ilde{
u}$ and $E_{	ext{ZPE}} =  rac{1}{2} h c 	ilde{
u}$ for a single harmonic mode, with $h = 6.62607015 	imes 10^{-34}\ \mathrm{J\,s}$, $c = 2.99792458 	imes 10^{10}\ \mathrm{cm\,s}^{-1}$, and $N_{	ext{A}} = 6.02214076 	imes 10^{23}\ \mathrm{mol}^{-1}$. You may equivalently use the conversion $1\ \mathrm{cm}^{-1} = 0.01196266\ \mathrm{kJ\,mol}^{-1}$. Briefly justify, in words, how this zero-point energy change is expected to impact the apparent free energy barrier $\Delta G^{\ddagger}$ at $T=298\ \mathrm{K}$ within the harmonic approximation when all other modes are unchanged. Only the numerical value of $\Delta E_{	ext{ZPE}}$ will be graded as the final answer; the discussion should be included in your solution reasoning.
